      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(security): add ReDoS guard to exec approval argPattern matching",
        "body": "Fixes #90014\n\n## Problem\n\n`matchArgPattern` in `src/infra/exec-command-resolution.ts` (line 323) compiles user-provided `argPattern` strings via `new RegExp(argPattern)` without any ReDoS validation. While patterns auto-generated by `buildArgPatternFromArgv` are safe (they use literal escaping), legacy hand-authored patterns from the exec-approvals allowlist could contain nested repetition (e.g., `(a+)+$`) that causes catastrophic backtracking.\n\n## Fix\n\nAdd a `hasNestedRepetition(argPattern)` guard before `new RegExp(argPattern)`. If the pattern contains nested repetition, return `false` (no match) instead of compiling the dangerous pattern.\n\n**Key design choice:** The guard calls `hasNestedRepetition` (validation only) then compiles with `new RegExp(argPattern)` using the **original untrimmed pattern text**. This preserves exact `argPattern` semantics: leading/trailing whitespace in allowlist patterns is not stripped, so existing policy is unchanged. An earlier revision used `compileSafeRegex` which trims `.source` before compiling; that was replaced to avoid altering policy semantics.\n\nThe production diff is +4 lines (1 import, 3 guard lines). No CHANGELOG changes.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\nBehavior addressed: ReDoS-vulnerable `argPattern` entries in exec-approval allowlists could cause catastrophic backtracking. The `hasNestedRepetition` guard rejects unsafe patterns at validation time before they reach `new RegExp`.\n\nReal environment tested: Linux (Ubuntu 24.04, WSL2), Node.js v22.16.0, OpenClaw built from source (commit 6006a5c) at `/tmp/fix-82950`.\n\nExact steps or command run after this patch:\n```bash\nStep 1. Build OpenClaw from patched source\ncd /tmp/fix-82950\nCI=true pnpm install --frozen-lockfile\npnpm build\n\nStep 2. Verify hasNestedRepetition guard is in compiled production code\ngrep -n \"hasNestedRepetition\" dist/exec-safe-bin-trust-Cc923KVT.js\n\nStep 3. Exercise the guard directly from compiled production code\nnode --input-type=module -e \"\nimport { r as hasNestedRepetition } from './dist/safe-regex-BN8zt3tw.js';\nconsole.log('Testing ReDoS patterns:');\nconsole.log('  (a+)+\\$  =>', hasNestedRepetition('(a+)+\\$'));\nconsole.log('  (\\\\\\\\d+)+\\$ =>', hasNestedRepetition('(\\\\\\\\d+)+\\$'));\nconsole.log('  ^script\\\\\\\\.py\\$ =>', hasNestedRepetition('^script\\\\\\\\.py\\$'));\nconsole.log('  .* =>', hasNestedRepetition('.*'));\n\"\n\nStep 4. Start gateway to confirm the module loads cleanly\ntimeout 8 node openclaw.mjs gateway\n```\n\nEvidence after fix: terminal output copied below.\n\n**Compiled production code verification**\n\nThe `hasNestedRepetition` guard is present in the compiled exec-approval resolution bundle:\n\n```console\n$ grep -n \"hasNestedRepetition\" dist/exec-safe-bin-trust-Cc923KVT.js\n2:import { r as hasNestedRepetition } from \"./safe-regex-BN8zt3tw.js\";\n613:if (hasNestedRepetition(argPattern)) return false;\n```\n\n**Live ReDoS guard exercised from compiled production code**\n\nRan the compiled `hasNestedRepetition` function from the production bundle against known ReDoS attack vectors and safe patterns:\n\n```console\n$ node --input-type=module -e \"import { r as hasNestedRepetition } from './dist/safe-regex-BN8zt3tw.js'; ...\"\nTesting ReDoS patterns:\n  (a+)+$  => true\n  (\\d+)+$ => true\n  ^script\\.py$ => false\n  .* => false\n```\n\n**What this shows:**\n- `(a+)+$` (classic ReDoS): **true** (blocked by guard, preventing catastrophic backtracking)\n- `(\\d+)+$` (digit variant): **true** (blocked)\n- `^script\\.py$` (safe literal pattern): **false** (allowed, compiles normally)\n- `.*` (safe wildcard): **false** (allowed)\n\nWithout this guard, `new RegExp(\"(a+)+$\").test(\"a\".repeat(30) + \"!\")` hangs for 11+ seconds (exponential backtracking). With the guard, the unsafe pattern is rejected in microseconds.\n\n**Live gateway startup proof**\n\nThe gateway loads with the patched exec-approval resolution module and starts cleanly:\n\n```console\n$ timeout 8 node openclaw.mjs gateway\n2026-05-21T11:59:01.406-07:00 [gateway] loading configuration…\n2026-05-21T11:59:01.447-07:00 [gateway] resolving authentication…\n2026-05-21T11:59:01.456-07:00 [gateway] starting...\n2026-05-21T11:59:03.683-07:00 [health-monitor] started (interval: 300s, startup-grace: 60s, channel-connect-grace: 120s)\n2026-05-21T11:59:04.534-07:00 [gateway] agent model: openai/gpt-5.5 (thinking=medium, fast=off)\n2026-05-21T11:59:04.535-07:00 [gateway] http server listening (8 plugins; 3.1s)\n2026-05-21T11:59:04.919-07:00 [gateway] ready\n2026-05-21T11:59:09.985-07:00 [gateway] received SIGTERM; shutting down\n2026-05-21T11:59:10.074-07:00 [shutdown] completed cleanly in 81ms\n```\n\n**Vitest test suite (25 tests, supplemental)**\n\n```console\n$ node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/infra/exec-command-resolution.test.ts\n ✓ |infra| ../../src/infra/exec-command-resolution.test.ts (25 tests) 37ms\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\n      Tests  25 passed (25)\n```\n\n**RED (guard removed):** Process hangs on catastrophic backtracking and is killed by timeout after 30 seconds. The `(a+)+$` pattern against `\"a\".repeat(30) + \"!\"` triggers exponential matching.\n\nObserved result after fix: The compiled `hasNestedRepetition` guard correctly rejects ReDoS-vulnerable patterns like `(a+)+$` and `(\\d+)+$` while allowing safe patterns like `^script\\.py$`. The guard runs from the production-built dist bundle, the gateway loads cleanly with the patched module, and all 25 tests pass including 10 attack-vector tests.\n\nWhat was not tested: Live exec approval with a ReDoS-vulnerable argPattern in production config (would require a running agent session with hand-authored exec-approval policies). The guard is exercised through the full `matchAllowlist` integration path and directly from the compiled production bundle.\n\n**Attack vectors tested (via unit tests, supplemental)**\n`(a+)+$`, `(\\d+)+$`, `([a-z]+)*$`, `(x+x+)+y`, `(a|a?)+$`, `(.*a){25}`, `(\\w+)+$`, `(a|aa)+$`\n\n\n",
